\id ESG  
\h Esther 
\toc1 Esther (Greek AT) 
\toc2 Esther (GreekAT) 
\toc3 EsGA 
\mt1 Esther  
\mt2 translated from the Greek Alpha Text
\c A
\p 
\v 1 In the second year of the reign of Ahasuerus the great, on the first day of the month Adar-Nisan (which is Dystros-Xanthikos.\f + \fr A:1 \ft Adar-Nisan refers to months on the Hebrew calendar, Dystros-Xanthikos refers to months on the Macedonian calendar.\f*) Mordecai the son of Jair, son of Shimei, son of Kish, of the tribe of Benjamin, a great man, had a dream.
\v 2 He was one of the captives whom Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon had carried captive with Jeconiah the king of Judah.
\v 3 This was his dream: Behold, a voice and a shout of tumult: thunders and earthquake and upheaval on the earth.
\v 4 And behold, two great serpents, and they both came out to fight,
\v 5 And a voice came from them, and everything was thrown into turmoil by the sound of their cry.
\v 6 A day of darkness and gloom and turmoil of war was witnessed by all people, and every nation prepared for war, and we cried to the Lord because of the sound of their cry.
\v 7 And from a little spring came much water---a great river.
\v 8 Light! The sun arose, and the rivers rose and swallowed up the mighty.
\p 
\v 9 And Mordecai, having risen from his sleep, pondered what the dream meant and what the Mighty One was preparing to do.
\v 10 His dream was hidden in his heart, and he continually sought to understand it.
\v 11 Its interpretation would be made clear to him on the day when Mordecai slept in the court of the king with Astau and Thedeutus, the king’s two eunuchs
\v 12 and heard their conversation and their plotting, as they were discussing attacking king Ahasuerus to kill him.
\v 13 Mordecai, having carefully considered it, reported them.
\v 14 The king examined the two eunuchs and found Mordecai’s report true. After they confessed, the eunuchs were led away.
\v 15 King Ahasuerus wrote about these things, and Mordecai was written in the royal records so these things might be remembered,
\v 16 and the king commanded that Mordecai should serve him in the court of the king, and guard at every gate in a prominent position.
\p 
\v 17 And in connection with these matters Haman son of Hamadatha, a Macedonian, was brought before the king.\f + \fr A:17 \ft The Greek here is tricky and its meaning is debated. An alternate translation might be, “And in connection with these matters he presented to him Haman son of Hamadatha, a Macedonian, before the king.”\f*
\v 18 But Haman was seeking to harm Mordecai and all his people because he had spoken to the king about the eunuchs, because they had been executed.

\c 1  
\p
\v 1 And it came to pass after these things in the days of Ahasuerus the great king,---(from India to Ethiopia, one hundred twenty-seven provinces were subject to him)---
\v 2 when Ahasuerus was sitting on his royal throne,
\v 3 the king made a banquet for the court princes of Persia and Media, and the governors of the provinces, in his presence
\v 4 to show the wealth of the king's glory and the splendour of his pride for one hundred and eighty days.
\p
\v 5 When the days were completed which the king had arranged, for all who were found in the city of Susa, from the greatest to the least, he gave a banquet for seven days inside the king’s court, celebrating his prosperity.
\v 6 There were coverings spread out, linen, cotton, violet and scarlet fabrics interwoven with floral designs, a pavillion stretched out with linen and purple cords set in silver bases, marble and gilded pillars, golden couches on an emerald pavement and roses all around.
\v 7 Golden goblets of exceptional workmanship were used, and royal wine—the kind the king himself drinks.
\v 8 The drinking was according to law, for the king had ordered that each person be allowed to do as he wished.
\p
\v 9 And Queen Vashti held a great banquet for all the women in the king’s court.
\p
\v 10 Now on the seventh day, when the king was merry with wine, he told his attendants, 
\v 11 to bring Queen Vashti to the banquet in progress wearing her royal crown, before his assembled company,
\v 12 but Vashti refused to do the king’s will as conveyed by the eunuchs.
\p When the king heard that Vashti had rejected\f + \fr 1:12 \ft The word here is stronger than ‘refuse’; it implies invalidating the king's command.\f* his decision, he was deeply troubled, and anger burned within him.
\v 13 And the king said to all the wise men who know law and judgment, “What should be done to the queen because she was unwilling to do the king’s will?”
\v 14 Then the princes of Persia and Media approached him—the officials who have access to the king’s presence and who sit in the royal court,
\v 16 and Bougaios advised him, saying, “Queen Vashti has wronged not only the king but also the princes of Persia and Media, and her offence will spread to all the peoples, because she has rejected the king’s decree.
\v 18 If therefore it seems good to our lord and pleases his judgment, let a decree be written to all the provinces and to all the peoples, declaring that Vashti rejected the king’s command, and let the queenship be given to another woman better than she.
\v 20 Let her be seen obeying the king’s command, and this will be good for all the kingdoms; and all women will give honour and respect to their husbands, from the poorest to the richest.”
\p 
\v 21 This advice pleased the king and he carried it out readily.

\c 2
\p
\v 1 So the matter of Vashti and what she had done to king Ahasuerus stood in remembrance. 
\v 2 And the king’s attendants said, “Let beautiful virgins be sought, and let them be placed under the supervision of Gogaios the eunuch, the keeper of the women, 
\v 4 and the girl who pleases the king will take Vashti's place.” And they promptly acted accordingly. 
\p
\v 5 Now in the city of Susa there was a Jewish man named Mordecai, the son of Jairus, the son of Shimei, the son of Kish, of the tribe of Benjamin.
\v 7 He was faithfully raising Esther, the daughter of his father’s brother; and the girl was exceedingly beautiful in form and attractive in appearance.
\v 8 The girl was taken into the king’s house, and Bugaeus the eunuch who was in charge of the women saw her; and she pleased him more than all the women.
\v 9 Esther found favour and kindness before him, and he was quick to provide for her and assigned her more than the usual seven attendants, her chosen girls. When Esther was brought before the king, she pleased him greatly.
\v 14 When evening came she would be brought in, and in the morning she would be sent away.
\v 17 When the king had been with all the virgins, Esther proved the most distinguished. She found favour and kindness before him, and he placed the royal crown upon her head.
\v 18 The king celebrated Esther’s wedding with great splendour and granted remissions to all the provinces.

\c 3
\p
\v 1 After these events King Ahasuerus promoted Haman son of Hamadatha the Bougaean. He elevated him and placed his seat above those of the other officials, so that everyone bowed and prostrated themselves before him to the ground.
\v 2 With everyone bowing to him according to the king’s command, Mordecai did not bow to him.
\v 3 The king’s servants saw that Mordecai was not bowing to Haman, and they said to him, “Why are you disobeying the king and not bowing to Haman?”
\v 4 He told them that he was a Jew, and they reported this about him to Haman.
\p
\v 5 When Haman heard this, he became angry with Mordecai, and rage blazed within him. He sought to kill Mordecai and all his people in a single day.
\v 6 Haman, burning with jealousy and stirred up with all his anger, became red with rage. Turning him away from his sight, he spoke maliciously to the king about Israel,
\v 8 \f + \fr 3:8 \ft The out of sequence verse numbering is as it appears in the  Göttingen edition.\f*saying, “There is a people scattered among all the kingdoms, a rebellious and warlike people with strange customs. They pay no attention to your laws, O king, and do not submit to you. They are recognised by all the nations as being wicked and they reject your decrees to undermine your glory.
\v 9 So if it pleases the king, and the decision seems good to him, let this people be given to me for destruction, and I will deposit ten thousand talents of silver into the royal treasury.”
\v 11 The king said to him, “Keep the silver, but deal with the people however you like.”
\v 10 \f + \fr 3:10 \ft Verse 10 appears after verse 11 in the AT, but the contents loosely match verse 10 of the MT and LXX.\f*The king removed the ring from his hand and gave it to Haman, saying, “Write to all the provinces and seal it with the king’s ring, for no one can revoke the seal.”
\p
\v 7 \f + \fr 3:7 \ft Verse 7 appears after verse 10 in the AT, but the contents loosely match verse 7 of the MT and LXX.\f*Haman went to his gods to determine the day of their death, and he cast lots for the thirteenth day of the month Adar–Nisan, to kill all the Jews, from male to female, and to carry off the children.
\v 13 He hurried and handed it over to mounted couriers.
\p
\v 14 The great king Ahasuerus signed the following letter to the governors and satraps of the one hundred and twenty-seven provinces from India to Ethiopia, writing as follows:
\p
\v 15 “Having ruled over many nations and gained dominion over the whole inhabited world, I resolved—without being lifted up by the arrogance of power, but governing with moderation and gentleness—to establish the lives of my subjects in continual peace and to make the kingdom mild and accessible to its furthest limits, renewing the peace desired by all people.
\v 16 When I asked my counsellors how this might be brought to completion, Haman—who among us has distinguished himself for prudence, with unwavering goodwill and firm loyalty, and who has received the second rank in the kingdom—
\v 16a pointed out to us that there exists a certain hostile people, living as aliens scattered among all the nations of the world, opposing the laws of every nation and continually disregarding the decrees of the kings, so that the kingdom may never enjoy stability.
\v 17 Therefore, recognizing that this nation stands alone—opposed to the way of life of all peoples, since its laws produce an alien manner of life—and that it is hostile toward our decrees, continually bringing about the worst evils so that the monarchy governed by us may never be securely established
\v 18 Therefore we have ordered you to destroy utterly those designated to you in the written instructions of Haman (who has been appointed over affairs and is our second father), root and branch, together with their women and children, by the swords of their enemies, without any pity or mercy, on the fourteenth day of the twelfth month (that is, the month Adar, called Dystros), killing all the Jews and seizing their children, so that those long hostile to us may in a single day descend to Hades, and the future may become stable and no longer bring us continual trouble.”
\p
\v 19 And this decree was publicly posted in Susa.

\c 4
\p
\v 1 But Mordecai learned everything that had happened. The city of Susa was thrown into turmoil because of these events, and among all the Jews there was great and bitter mourning in every city.
\p 
\v 2 But Mordecai went home, removed his garments, and clothed himself with sackcloth and ashes. Then he went out toward the outer court and stood there, for he could not enter the royal palace wearing sackcloth.
\v 3 He called one of the eunuchs and sent him to Esther. The queen said, “Remove his sackcloth and bring him in.”
But Mordecai said, “Tell her this: Do not refuse to go in to the king and seek his favour for me and for the people. Remember the days of your humble condition when you were brought up under my care, for Haman, who is second in authority, has spoken to the king against us, seeking our death.”
\v 5 Call upon God, speak to the king on our behalf, and deliver us from death.”
\v 6 And he reported to her the distress of Israel.
\v 7 She sent this message to him: “You know better than anyone that whoever enters the king’s presence without being summoned—if he does not extend his golden sceptre—will be liable to death.
\v 8 I have not been summoned to him for thirty days now. How can I now go in while unsummoned?”
\v 9 Mordecai sent this reply to her: “If you ignore your people and refuse to help them, God will be their helper and deliverance; but you and your father’s house will perish. 
\v 10 And who knows if you became queen for just this moment?”
\v 11 The queen sent this reply:
\v 11a “Command acts of devotion and pray earnestly to God. I and my maidens will do the same. Then I will go in to the king, though I have not been summoned—even if it means that I must die.”
\p
\v 12 And Mordecai did so.
\v 12a He prayed to the Lord, remembering his deeds, and said:
\p
\v 13 “Lord Almighty, in whose power are all things,
and no one can oppose you when you choose to save the house of Israel.
\v 13a For you made heaven and earth and every wondrous thing under heaven,
\v 13b and you rule over all. 
\v 14 For you know all things;
you know the people of Israel.” 
\v 15 “It was not out of arrogance or ambition that I refused to bow to the uncircumcised Haman. I would even have been willing to kiss the soles of his feet for the sake of Israel.
\v 15a But I acted so that I would place no one before your glory, O Lord, and bow to no one except you, the true God; nor will I do so even under pressure.” 
\v 16 And now, Lord who made covenant with Abraham,
spare your people, for they have risen against us to destroy us,
and they desire to annihilate and wipe out your inheritance from the beginning. 
\v 16a Do not abandon your portion—the people you redeemed from the land of Egypt.
\v 17 Hear our plea and be merciful to your inheritance.
Turn our mourning into joy,
so that we may live and praise you;
do not silence the mouths of those who praise you.”
\p
\v 18 Queen Esther took refuge in the Lord, seized with mortal anguish.
\v 18a She removed her royal garments and every sign of her splendour, and clothed herself with distress and mourning. Instead of her luxurious perfumes she covered her head with ashes and dung, and she greatly humbled her body. Every sign of her adornment and the beauty of her hair she replaced with humiliation.
\v 19 She prayed to the Lord and said:
\p
“O Lord, King,
you alone are my helper.
Help me, humble as I am
and with no helper but you,
\v 19a for I am risking my life.
\v 20 But I have heard in the record of my ancestors that you redeemed Israel from all the nations and chose their fathers from among their forefathers, making Israel your everlasting inheritance. And you fulfilled for them what you promised and granted what they asked.
\p
\v 21 We have sinned against you, and you handed us over into the hands of our enemies,
\v 21a because we honoured their gods. 
\v 22 You are righteous, O Lord. Yet now they have not been satisfied with the bitterness of our slavery, but have joined their hands with those of their idols
\v 22a in order to abolish the decree of your mouth, to destroy your inheritance, to shut the mouths of those who praise you, and to extinguish the glory of your house and your altar.
\v 22b They would open the mouths of enemies to praise worthless gods and cause a mortal king to be glorified forever.
\p
\v 23 Do not, O Lord, hand over your sceptre
to enemies who hate you,
and do not let them rejoice
at our downfall.
Turn their plans against them,
and make an example of the one
who began this evil against us. 
\v 24 Appear to us, O Lord;
make yourself known to us
in our time of distress,
and do not let us be crushed. 
\v 25 Give fitting words to my mouth,
and grant favour to my speech
before the king.
Turn his heart to hatred
of the one who makes war against us,
to the destruction of him
and of those who agree with him.
\v 25a But deliver us by your mighty hand,
and help me,
for you know all things.
\v 25b You know that I detest the bed
of an uncircumcised man,
and that I hate the glory
of the lawless and of every foreigner.
\p
\v 26 “You, Lord, know my necessity: I detest the symbol of pride that rests upon my head. I do not wear it except on the day when I must appear, and I loathe it like the menstral rag.
\v 27 Your servant has not eaten with them at their tables.
\v 28 I have taken no pleasure in the king’s banquets, nor have I drunk the wine of libations. Your servant has found no joy since my change of station except in you, O Lord. 
\v 29 And now, you who are mighty over all, hear the cry of the desperate and deliver us from the hand of those plotting evil against us. Rescue me also, Lord, from the power of my fear.”

\c 5
\p
\v 1 On the third day, when Esther had finished praying, she removed her garments of mourning and put on her royal garments.
\v 2 And appearing in splendour, and after calling upon God, the knower of all things and saviour, she took with her two maidservants. She leaned on one of them as though she were delicate, while the other followed behind, lifting the train of her robe.
\v 3 She was blushing in the full bloom of her beauty; her face was lovely, but her heart was distressed. 
\p
\v 4 After entering through the doors she stood before the king. The king was seated on the throne of his kingdom, dressed in all his splendour, covered with gold and precious stones, and he was exceedingly fearsome.
\v 5 And lifting his face, blazing with splendour, he fixed his gaze on her like a bull at the height of its fury.
\v 6 The queen was overcome with fear; her face changed as she began to faint, and she leaned upon the head of the maidservant who walked before her.
\v 7 God changed the king’s spirit and turned his anger into gentleness.
\v 8 The king, alarmed, leapt down from his throne, took her in his arms, and comforted her.
\v 8a What is it, Esther? I am your brother.
\v 9 Take courage. You will certainly not die, for this matter concerns us both. The threat is not against you. Look—the sceptre is in your hand. 
\p 
\v 10 Then he raised the sceptre and touched her neck with it, kissed her, and said, “Speak to me.” 
\p 
\v 11 She said to him, “I saw you as an angel of God, and my heart melted from the majesty of your anger, my lord.” 
\v 12 and beads of sweat stood upon her face.
\p The king was alarmed, and all his attendants as well, and they tried to comfort her.
\v 13 And the king said, “What is it, Esther? Tell me, and I will grant it—even up to half my kingdom.”
\p 
\v 14 Esther said, “Tomorrow is a special day for me. If it pleases the king, let the king and Haman your friend come to the banquet that I will prepare tomorrow.” 
\p 
\v 15 So the king said, “Summon Haman at once, so that we may carry out Esther’s request,”
\v 16 and both of them came to the banquet that Esther had prepared, a sumptuous feast.
\v 17 And the king said to Esther, “Queen, what is your wish? Ask—even up to half my kingdom—and it shall be yours, whatever you request.” 
\v 18 And Esther said, “This is my request and my petition: 
\v 18a “If I have found favour before you, O king, and if it pleases the king to grant my request and fulfil my petition, let the king and Haman come to the banquet that I will prepare for them tomorrow. Then tomorrow I will as you say.”
\v 19 So the king said, “Do as you wish.”
\p
\v 20 Haman was informed of the same thing and was astonished; and the king, having withdrawn, retired to rest. 
\v 21 But Haman went home and gathered together his friends, his sons, and Zosara his wife,
\v 21a and he boasted, “The queen invited no one to her special banquet except the king and me alone—and tomorrow I am invited again.
\v 22 Only one thing bothers me: whenever I see Mordecai the Jew in the king’s court, he refuses to bow to me.”
\p
\v 23 His wife Zosara said to him, “He belongs to the Jewish people. Since the king has permitted you to destroy the Jews, and the gods have granted you a day of ruin for vengeance upon them, have a pole fifty cubits high cut and set up. Hang him on the pole, then rise early and speak to the king about it. Now go in and enjoy yourself with the king.”
\p 
\v 24 Haman liked the idea and acted accordingly.

\c 6
\p
\v 1 But the Mighty One drove sleep from the king that night, and he lay awake,
\v 2 so the readers were summoned, and the book of records was read to him.
\v 3 There was recorded the matter of the eunuchs and the service Mordecai had rendered the king. 
\v 4 The king gave the matter serious thought and said, “Mordecai is a faithful man who protected my life, for it is through him that I am alive today and sit upon my throne. Yet I have done nothing for him. I have not acted rightly.” 
\v 5 And the king said to his attendants, “What shall we do for Mordecai, who saved me in this matter?” When the young men realised this, they resented him, for the fear of Haman lay deep within them. 
\v 6 The king understood. Then morning came.
\v 6a The king asked, “Who is outside?” And it was Haman.
\p
\v 7 But Haman had come early to speak with the king in order to have Mordecai hanged. 
\v 8 The king said, “Bring him in.”
\v 9 When he entered, the king said to him, “What should be done for the man who honours the king — the one whom the king wishes to exalt?” 
\v 10 And Haman thought to himself, "Who would the king wish to exalt but me?"
\p
\v 11 And Haman said, “For the man whom the king wishes to exalt,
\v 11a Let them bring a royal robe and a royal horse that the king himself rides, 
\v 11b And let one of the nobles, one of the king’s friends, take these things and clothe the man and mount him on the horse, and lead him through the city, proclaiming before him: ‘Thus shall it be done for the man who honours the king — the one whom the king wishes to exalt.’”
\v 12 The king said to Haman, “Quick! Run and take the horse and the robe just as you described, and do this for Mordecai the Jew who sits at the gate. Leave out nothing of what you said.”
\v 13 When Haman realised that he himself was not the one being exalted but Mordecai, his heart was crushed, and his spirit sank in dejection.
\p
\v 14 So Haman took the robe and the horse, ashamed before Mordecai, since on that very day he had decided to impale him,
\v 15 And he said to Mordecai, “Remove your sackcloth.”
\v 16 Mordecai was greatly troubled, as though facing death, and with anguish he took off the sackcloth and put on garments of splendour.
\v 17 Mordecai felt as though he were seeing a marvel, and his heart turned to the Lord, and he stood speechless in astonishment. 
\v 18 And Haman hurried to mount him on the horse. 
\v 19 Haman led the horse out and conducted him along, proclaiming, “Thus shall it be done for the man who honours the king, whom the king wishes to exalt.”
\p
\v 20 Haman, for his part, went home downcast, but Mordecai went to his house.
\v 21 Haman told his wife all that had happened to him
\v 22 His wife and his advisers said, “Ever since you began speaking evil against him, misfortune has been coming upon you. Leave it alone, for God is with them.”
\v 23 While they were still speaking, someone arrived to summon him to the banquet, urging him to hurry, and so he cheered up.
\v 23a And he went and reclined with them at the appointed hour.

\c 7
\p
 
\v 1 As the drinking progressed, the king said to Esther, “What danger do you face, and what is your request? Even up to half my kingdom.” 
\v 2 Esther was in anguish as she spoke, because the adversary stood before her; but God gave her courage as she called upon him.
\v 3 If it seems good to the king, and if he judges it right, let my people be granted to me at my request—the nation that is my very life. 
\v 4 For my people and I have been sold into slavery, and their infants to be plundered. I did not wish to trouble my lord with it, for the man who has harmed us would himself fall.
\v 5 The king became angry and said, “Who is this man who dared to dishonour the symbol of my kingship and cast aside the fear owed to you?”
\v 6 When the queen saw that the king was greatly disturbed and angered at the wrongdoing, she said, “Do not be angry, my lord. It is enough that I have received your favour. Enjoy the banquet, O king; tomorrow I will answer according to your command.”
\v 7 The king swore that she must reveal to him the man who had presumptuously done this, and with an oath he promised to do for her whatever she wished. 
\v 8 Then Esther, taking courage, said, “Haman—your friend—the deceiver: this man here, this wicked man.”
\p
\v 9 The king, furious and filled with rage, sprang to his feet and began pacing about.
\v 10 Haman, terrified, threw himself at the feet of Esther the queen as she was still reclining on the couch.
\v 11 The king returned to the banquet and, seeing this, said, “Was the offence against the kingdom not enough for you, that you would even violate my wife before my eyes? Take Haman away—he shall not live.” 
\v 12 So he was led away.
\p
\v 12a Agathas, one of the king’s attendants, said, “Look, there is a gallows fifty cubits high in Haman’s courtyard, which he prepared to hang Mordecai—the man who spoke for the king’s good. Command, my lord, that he be hanged on it.”
\v 13 The king said, “Hang him on it.” Then the king removed the ring from his hand, and with it his fate was sealed. 
\v 14 \f + \fr 7:14 \ft After chapter 7 the text of the AT diverges from the other versions. The Göttingen edition has no more chapter breaks after chapter 7 and numbers all the remaining verses consecutively. \f*The king said to Esther, “And he planned to hang Mordecai—the man who saved me from the hands of the eunuchs? Did he not know that Esther belongs to his own family?”
\p
\v 15 The king summoned Mordecai and granted him all of Haman’s possessions. 
\v 16 “He said to him, “What do you wish? I will grant it.” And Mordecai said, “That you revoke Haman’s letter.”
\v 17 The king placed the affairs of the kingdom in his hands.
\p
\v 18 And the next day Esther said to the king,
“Grant me the right to execute my enemies.”
\v 19 Then Queen Esther petitioned the king also against the sons of Haman, that they too might die along with their father. And the king said, “Let it be done.”
\v 20 And he struck down the enemies in great numbers.
\v 21 In Susa the king granted the queen’s request that the men be executed, and he said, “See, I grant you the right to hang them.” And it was done.

\p 
\v 22 And he wrote the following letter:
\v 22a “The great king Assuerus to the rulers and satraps of the one hundred and twenty-seven provinces from India to Ethiopia who are loyal to us: greetings.
\v 23 Many who are honoured again and again by the great generosity of their benefactors grow proud.
They seek to harm not only those subject to us, but, unable to restrain their arrogance, they even attempt to plot evil against their own benefactors.
\v 23a Not only do they destroy gratitude among men, but, carried away by the empty flatteries of the naive, they imagine they will escape the punishment of the righteous judge who rules over all and hates wickedness.
\v 23b Often those appointed to positions of authority to manage the affairs of trusted friends become guilty of innocent blood and plunge others into irreparable disasters,
\v 23c deceiving the sincere goodwill of those in authority by their wicked deceit. 
\v 24 It may be seen both from the histories handed down to us and from what lies plainly before our eyes how cruel those in power may prove to be.
\v 24a Therefore rulers must take thought for the future and maintain the kingdom in peace and stability for all the nations,
\v 24b not making use of accusations, but handling the matters brought before them with fairness.
\p
\v 25 For Haman son of Hamadatha, the Bougaean, although welcomed among us, was in truth alien to the spirit of the Persians and far removed from our own clemency.
\v 25a He enjoyed the benevolence we extend from ourselves to every nation to such a degree that he was proclaimed our “father”, honoured by all, and continued to hold the second place among the royal thrones.
\v 26 He enjoyed the benevolence we extend from ourselves to every nation to such a degree that he was proclaimed our “father”, honoured by all, and continued to hold the second place among the royal thrones.
\v 26a Yet he contrived by devious schemes to bring to destruction Mordecai, our constant saviour, and Esther his blameless companion, together with their entire nation.
\v 26b For by these schemes he supposed that, once we had been left defenceless, he could transfer the sovereignty of the Persians to the Macedonians. 
\v 27 Therefore we find that the Jews, who had been handed over to you by that thrice-accursed man, are not criminals but live according to the most just laws,
\v 27a and that they are also sons of the only and true God, who has guided our kingdom until now in the most excellent order.
\p
\v 28 Therefore you have done well in disregarding the letters previously sent to you by Haman,
since the very man who perpetrated these things has been impaled at the gates of Susa, the Judge who sees all things having repaid him with the punishment he deserved.
\v 29 Let a copy of this letter be posted in every place, and let the Jews make use of their own laws 
and to support them, so that they may defend themselves against those who attack them in the time of distress.
\p
\v 30 And it was decided by the Jews throughout the kingdom to observe the fourteenth day of the month, which is Adar, and to celebrate on the fifteenth
because on those days the Almighty brought them deliverance and rejoicing. 
\v 31 And now after these things they bring deliverance to the Persians, but for those who plotted against them they stand as a memorial of destruction.
\v 32 But any city or region that does not act in accordance with these things will be consumed with spear and fire in wrath, and it will be laid waste, becoming inaccessible not only to men but also to beasts and birds.
\v 33 And it was also posted in Susa, a proclamation containing these words; and the king entrusted Mordecai to write whatever he wished.
\v 34 And Mordecai sent out letters, sealing them with the king’s signet ring, that his people should remain each in their own provinces and celebrate a festival to God.
\v 35 And the letter which Mordecai sent contained the following:
\v 36 Haman sent you letters stating as follows: “The Jewish nation is rebellious. Make haste and send them to me for destruction.”
\v 37 But I, Mordecai, inform you that the man who carried out these things has been hanged at the gates of Susa, and his house has been confiscated.
\v 38 For this man intended to kill us on the thirteenth day of the month, which is Adar.
\p
\v 39 And Mordecai went out arrayed in the royal robe and wearing a diadem of fine linen and purple. 
\v 40 And the people in Susa rejoiced when they saw it,
\v 40a and for the Jews there was light, drinking, and festivity,
\v 41 and many of the people were circumcised and became Jews, and no one rose up against them, for they feared them.
\p
\v 42 And the governors and rulers and satraps and the royal scribes honoured the Jews, for the fear of Mordecai had fallen upon them.
\v 43 And in Susa the name of Haman and of those opposed to the Jews was proclaimed throughout the whole kingdom. 
\v 44 And in Susa the Jews killed seven hundred men.
\v 44a including Pharsan and his brother and Pharga,
\v 44b and Gagaphardatha,
\v 44c and Marmasima and Izathuth,
\v 44d and the ten sons of Haman son of Hamadathos the Bougaean, the enemy of the Jews, and they plundered all their possessions. 
\v 45 The king said to Esther, “How have those here and those in the surrounding region treated you?”
\v 46 Esther replied, “Let it be granted to the Jews to destroy and plunder whomever they wish.” And he granted it. 
\v 46a And they destroyed seventy thousand and one hundred men.
\p
\v 47 Mordecai wrote these things in a book and sent them to the Jews who were in the kingdom of Ahasuerus, both far and near, 
\v 47a to establish these days as days of praise and rejoicing instead of sorrow and mourning, the fourteenth and the fifteenth,
\v 48 and they sent portions to the poor, and they received them.
\v 49 For this reason these days were called Phoureia,\f + \fr 7:49 \ft Phoureia: a Greek version of the Hebrew Purim.\f* because of the lots that were cast for these days as a memorial.
\p
\v 50 The king recorded the tribute of the land and the sea
\v 50a and his power, and the wealth and glory of his kingdom. 
\v 51 And he exalted Mordecai, and it was written in the books of the Persians and the Medes as a memorial. 
\v 52 And Mordecai stood next to King Ahasuerus and he was great in the kingdom and beloved by all the Jews, and he led them and brought honour to all his people.
\p
\v 53 And Mordecai said, “These things have come from God.”
\v 54 For he remembered the dream which he had seen, and it was fulfilled, and he said:
\v 54a The little spring is Esther,
\v 54b and the two great serpents are Haman and I;
\v 54c The river is the nations that gathered together to destroy the Jews; the sun and the light that came to the Jews is the manifestation of God — this is the judgment. 
\v 55 And God performed these signs and wonders, which had never occurred among the nations.
\v 55a And he made two lots, one for the people of God and one for the nations;
\v 56 And these two lots came to the appointed hour and time, the day of judgment before the Eternal over all the nations. 
\v 57 And God remembered his people and vindicated his inheritance.
\v 58 And all the people cried out with a loud voice and said, “Blessed are you, Lord, who remembered the covenants made with our fathers. Amen.”
\v 59 And these days shall be for them, on the fourteenth and fifteenth of the month Adar, with assembly and joy and gladness before God, throughout their generations forever among his people Israel.

